SIMPLE: minuet
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Minuet
<hw>Min"u*et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr.
<ets>menu</ets> small, L. <ets>minutus</ets> small. So called on account
of the short steps of the dance. See 4th <er>Minute</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A slow graceful dance consisting of a coupee, a high
step, and a balance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A tune or air to regulate the
movements of the dance so called; a movement in suites, sonatas,
symphonies, etc., having the dance form, and commonly in 3-4, sometimes
3-8, measure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minum</ent>⟦br⟧
